Introduction

In the past classes we described how the mean and variance values could be used to describe the genetic architecture of a quantitative traits. Briefly, we also described about models that express the variation in terms of gametic or dosage models. Here, we will focus on the dosage models (also called Biometric model) and emphasize that genotypic variation can be divided into components due to additive and the dominance effects(G=A+D). Due to dominance, genotypes may not completely reflect the combinations of the alleles that make them up.

Theory

Dominance as deviations

Without using any model specification, we can theoretically express dominance as deviations. How? By considering it as a difference between the genotypic value and the breeding value for each genotype. As a simple example, we will expand some of the equations presented in the past classes. For the A1A1 genotype, the difference between the genotypic value and the population mean in equation is:

\[\begin{align*} M_G = a -[a(p-1)+ 2pqd]\\ M_G= 2q(a-dp)\\ D_{A1A1}= M_g - BV_{A1A1} \\ = 2q(a-dp) - BV \\ = 2q(a-dp) - 2q\alpha \\ = 2q(a-dp) - 2q(a+d(q-p)) \\ = 2qa -2qdp - 2qa -2q^2d + 2qdp \\ = -2q^2d \end{align*}\]

In summary:

Genotype A1A1 A1A2 A2A2
Genotypic value relative to midpoint +a d -a
Genotypic value relative to pop mean \(2q(a-dp)\) \(a(p+q)+d(1-2pq)\) \(-2p(a-dp)\)
Breeding Value \(2q\alpha\) \((q-p)\alpha\) \(-2p\alpha\)
Dominance -\(2q^2\)d 2pqd -2\(p^2\)d

For the sequence of this class, we will to discuss more theory about linear models. This is how Fisher, for example, originally described genetic variations.

Regression Biometric Model

Concepts related to Simple Linear Regression

Depending on the causal connections between two variables, x and y, the true relationship between both variables can be measured using linear regression.

In this case, we can represent it as:

\[y = \alpha + \beta x + e\] where \(\alpha\) is the y-intercept, \(\beta\) is the slope of the line (also known as the regression coefficient), and e is the residual error. When information on x is used to predict y, x is referred to as the predictor or independent variable and y as the response or dependent variable.

The objective of linear regression analysis is to estimate the model parameters, \(\alpha\) and \(\beta\), that give the “best fit” for the joint distribution of \(x\) and \(y\). With those estimated values, we can perform predictions and inference. By inference, we refer to the steps necessary of estimating the regression model and assesing uncertainty in the fit.

The mathematical method of least-squares linear regression provides one such best-fit solution. In short, without making any assumptions about the true joint distribution of x and y, least-squares finds soluction for the parameters that minimizes the average value of the error – deviations of the observed y from the values predicted by the regression line.

Below there is a graphical explanation of least-squares linear regression with some important considerations:

  • Straight lines can be drawn in multiple ways using different combinations of slope and intercept.
  • What is the best fit?
  • One way to solve this is to find the combination of slope and intercept that create a line and minimizes the error between the original and predicted values. Formally, finds the parameters values that minimizes the residual sum of squares.

Mathematically, the least-square solution for both \(\alpha\) and \(\beta\) can be computed as:

\[\alpha = \bar{y} - \hat{\beta}\bar{x}\] \[ \hat{\beta} = \dfrac{\sum (x_i-\bar{x})y_i}{\sum (x_i - \bar{x})^2} = \dfrac{Cov(x,y)}{Var(x)}\]

Thus, the least-squares estimators for the intercept and slope of a linear regression are simple functions of the observed means, variances, and covariances. From the standpoint of quantitative genetics, this property is exceedingly useful, since such statistics are readily obtainable from phenotypic data.

We can go further and represent in terms of variance. The goal is to determine how much of the variation is explained by the regression line and the error. Below, how this is represented in a classical ANOVA table:

Source of Variation Degrees of Freedom Sum of Squares Mean of Squares F-Ratio
Regression k SSreg = Σ(Ŷ - Ȳ)² MSreg = SSreg / k MSreg / MSres
Residual n-k-1 SSres = Σ(Y - Ŷ)² MSres = SSres / (n-k-1)
Total n-1 SStotal = Σ(Y - Ȳ)²

Where:

  • \(R2 = \dfrac{SSreg}{SStotal} = \dfrac{\hat{b}_1 \sum x_iy_i}{\sum y_i^2}\)

Biometric Model: dosage models

Intuition

Originally, Fisher (1918, 1930) defined the average effects of alleles from the linear regression of the genotypic values, weighted by their respective frequencies, on gene dose. This regression model was defined as Biometric Model. The connection between the genotypic values and the breeding values and dominance deviations can be graphically illustrated using least-squares regression. In the Biometric Model the genotypic value will be modelled as a function of the genotype (or the allele dosages) as presented in the Figure 1.

\[\begin{align*} b = \dfrac{Cov(x,y)}{V(x)}\\ Cov(x,y) = \sum f_i X_i Y_i - \sum f_iX_i \sum f_i Y_i\\ = 2pq[a+d(q-p)]\\ V(x) = \sum f_i X^2_i - (\mu_x)^2\\ = 2pq \\ b = \dfrac{Cov(x,y)}{V(x)} = a + d(q-p) = \alpha \end{align*}\]

Therefore, from a statistical point of view, the dominance deviation can be considered as a lack of adjustment to the linear prediction or, what is the same, as the interaction between the allelic effects for the determination of the genotypic value. We will see in future classes that this definition is the basis for modern association analyses (ex: GWAS).

Important:

  • The average effect of an allele substitution (\(\alpha\)) is equal to slope of regression line. It represents the average change in genotypic value per unit change in the number of alleles at the population level.
  • The original definition of the average effect of gene substitution was presented by Fisher (1918, 1941) in terms of linear regression.
  • Graphically, dominance can be interpreted as deviation from the breeding values.
  • In the absence of dominance, breeding values and genotypic values coincide.

Estimation theory: least squares

In the previous section we showed the intuition behind:

  • How variations in the allele dosages will affect the genotypic value.
  • How to connect additive and dominance effects based on expected values (breeding values) and deviations (dominance)

The sequence of this section requires some mathematical explanations that we cannot ignore. To this end, we will start with a simple representation of the genotypic values and allele frequencies, using the same principles discussed in the first three classes:

Genotype Genotypic Value (Y) Freq Alleles (X)
AA Y₁ = u + a p² 2
Aa Y₂ = u + d 2pq 1
aa Y₃ = u - a q² 0

Let’s compute the means:

\[\begin{align*} \overline{Y} = u + a(p-q) + 2pqd \\ = u + a(1-q-q) + 2pqd \\ = u + a(1-2q) + 2pqd\\ \overline{X} = p^2(2) + 2pq(1) + q^2(0) \\ =2p^2 + 2pq = 2p(p+q) = 2p\\ a = a + d(q-p) \\ = a + dq - dp\\ \end{align*}\]

We can keep moving it and represent it in a scaled version, where we will subtract the values by the population average, as follow:

Genotype AA

\[\begin{align*} y_1 = u + a\\ y_1 = Y_1 - \overline{Y}\\ = u + a - [u + a(p-q) + 2pqd] \\ = a - a(p-q) - 2pqd \\ = a - a(1-2q) - 2pqd \\ = a - a + 2qa - 2pqd = 2q(a-pd)\\ = 2q(a - dq)\\ \end{align*}\]

Genotype Aa \[\begin{align*} y_2 = u + d\\ y_2 = (u + d) - \mu_g\\ = u + d - [u + a(p-q) + 2pqd]\\ = u + d - u - a(1-2q) - 2pqd\\ = d - a(1-2q) - 2pqd\\ = d - a + 2qa - 2pqd \\ = d - a + 2qa - 2q^2d \\ = d - a + 2qa - 2q(1-p)d\\ = d - a + 2qa - 2qd + 2pqd \\ = d - (a - dq + dp) + 2qa - 2qd + 2pqd\\ = d - a - pd + 2qa - qd + 2pqd\\ = d - a - d(p+q) + 2qa + 2pqd \\ = a + 2qa + 2pqd\\ = a(-1+q+1-p) + 2pqd\\ = a(q-p) + 2pqd\\ \end{align*}\]

Genotype aa \[\begin{align*} Y_3 = u - a y_3 = Y_3 - \overline{Y}\\ = u - a - [u + a(p-q) + 2pqd] \\ = -a - a(p-q) - 2pqd\\ = -a - a(1-2q) - 2pqd\\ = -a - a + 2qa - 2pqd \\ = -2a + 2q(a - pd)\\ = -2a + 2q(a - qd)\\ = -2a + 2qa + 2q^2d\\ = -2(a - dq + pd) + 2q(a - qd)\\ = -2(a - dq + pd) + 2qa - 2q^2d \\ = -2a + 2qd - 2pd + 2qa - 2q^2d \\ = -2a(1-q) + 2d(q-p-q^2)\\ = -2pa + 2d[q-p-q(1-p)] \\ = -2pa + 2d(q-p-q+pq)\\ = -2pa + 2d[-p(1-q)]\\ = -2pa + 2d(-p^2)\\ = -2pa - 2p^2d\\ = -2p(a+pd) \end{align*}\]

Let’s represent it in a table, we are changing the values but they are only in a different scale. Therefore, if the variance in 100 in the Y metric, for the y the variance will be exactly the same.

Genotype Genotypic value (Y) Codified value(y)
AA Y₁ = u + a 2q(α-dq)
Aa Y₂ = u + d α(q-p) + 2pqd
aa Y₃ = u - a -2p(α+pd)

Now, we will carry out the same scaling process, but for the variable x, as follow:

  • \(x_1 = X_1 - \overline{X} = 2 - 2p = 2(1-p) = 2q\)
  • \(x_2 = X_2 - \overline{X} = 1 - 2p = 1 - p - p = q - p\)
  • \(x_3 = X_3 - \overline{X} = 0 - 2p = -2p\)

Thus, we can add one more column to the codified matrix that we are creating to express the Biometric Model:

Genotype Genotypic value (Y) Freq #alleles (X) y x
AA Y₁ = u + a p² 2 2q(a - dq) 2q
Aa Y₂ = u + d 2pq 1 α(q-p) + 2pqd q-p
aa Y₃ = u - a q² 0 -2p(α+pd) -2p

Now, we can use all these values, represented in terms of allele frequencies and scaled, in the context of regression analyses. We first need to write it as a regression model:

\[Y_i=\beta_0 + \beta_1X_i +e\] We will represent it as a codified version, by removing the average from the Y and X variable, as follow:

\[y_i = b_1x_i + d_i\] where: \(\hat{b}_1 = \dfrac{\sum x_iy_i}{\sum x_i^2}\)

Numerator of the equation

\[\begin{align*} \Sigma x^2_i = p^2(2q)^2 + 2pq(q-p)^2 + q^2(-2p)^2\\ = 4p^2q^2 + 2pq(q-p)^2 + 4p^2q^2\\ = 2pq[2pq + (q-p)^2 + 2pq]\\ = 2pq[2pq + q^2 - 2pq + p^2 + 2pq]\\ = 2pq(p^2 + 2pq + q^2)\\ = 2pq(p+q)^2\\ = 2pq \end{align*}\]

Denominator of the equation

\[\begin{align*} \Sigma x_iy_i = p^2(2q)[2(\alpha-qd)] + 2pq(q-p)[\alpha(q-p) + 2pqd] + q^2(-2p)[-2p\alpha + pd)]\\ = p^2(2q)^2(\alpha-qd) + 2pq\alpha(q-p)^2 + 2pq(q-p)(2pqd) + q^2(-2p)^2(\alpha+pd)\\ = 4p^2q^2(\alpha-qd) + 2pq\alpha(q-p)^2 + 4p^2q^2d(q-p) + 4p^2q^2(\alpha+pd)\\ = 4p^2q^2[2\alpha-d(q-p)] + 2pq\alpha(q-p)^2 + 4p^2q^2d(q-p)\\ = 4p^2q^2(2\alpha)-4p^2q^2d(q-p)+2pq\alpha(q-p)^{2}+4p^{2}q^{2}d(q-p)\\ = 4p^2q^2(2\alpha)+2pq\alpha(q^{2}-2pq+p^{2})\\ = 4p^2q^2(2\alpha)-4p^2q^2\alpha+2pq\alpha(p^{2}+q^{2})\\ = 4p^2q^2a + 2pq\alpha(p^2 + q^2)\\ = 2pq\alpha(2pq) + 2pq\alpha(p^2 + q^2)\\ = 2pq\alpha(p^2 + 2pq + q^2)\\ = 2pq\alpha \end{align*}\]

Thus, the most important:

\[\hat{b}_1 = \dfrac{\sum x_iy_i}{\sum x_i^2} = \dfrac{2pq\alpha}{2pq} = \alpha\]

Here we can show how we obtain the allele substitution effect from a classical regression analyses, using the Biometric Model. In a classical statistic class, this is called slope (or coefficient) of regression. This metric is fundamental for many aspects, and we already presented some reasons in the past topics. It measures the relationship between the genotypic value and the dosage of favorable alleles in a population. If this \(\alpha\) is different than zero – a fact that can be tested statistically.

We can write the predicted additive value (or the breeding value) by multiplying the terms as:

Genotype Genotypic value (Y) Freq #alleles (X) y x \(\hat{y}\)
AA Y₁ = u + a p² 2 2q(a - dq) 2q 2qα
Aa Y₂ = u + d 2pq 1 α(q-p) + 2pqd q-p α(q-p)
aa Y₃ = u - a q² 0 -2p(α+pd) -2p -2pα

In this context that we defined additivity, we will need also to remember our concepts related to dominance. Using classical genetic terms, the dominance is defined as the interaction between alleles from the same locus. Herein, we will define it as deviation from the expected additive values.

ANOVA analyses

After estimated the slopes using least squares, for the sequence of this class, we will approach the same regression model, but in the context of ANOVA models. The idea is to quantify the importance variation, by decomposing the genotypic variance in terms of regression and and residual.

At the mathematical level, this is our ultimate goal:

\[\sum y^2_i = \hat{b}_1\sum x_iy_i + \sum e^2_i \]

where:

  • \(\sum y^2_i\) = Total Sum of Squares (in statistical terms) or genotypic variance (at the genetic level)
  • \(\hat{b}_1\sum x_iy_i\) = Regression Sum of Squares (in statistical terms) or additive variance (at the genetic level)
  • \(\sum e^2_i\) = residual (in statistical terms) or dominance/deviation (at the genetic level)

Below, the sequence of mathematical derivations to decompose the sum of squares.

Total Sum of Squares

\[\sum f_iy_i^2 = p^2(y_1)^2 + 2pq (y_2)^2 + q^2(y_3)^2 = \sigma^2_g\]

\[\begin{align*} \sigma_g^2 = p^2[2q(\alpha-qd)]^2 + 2pq[\alpha(q-p) + 2pqd]^2 + q^2[-2p(\alpha + pd)]^2\\ = p^2[2q^2(\alpha-qd)^2] + 2pq[\alpha^2(q-p)^2 + (2pqd)^2 + 2\alpha(q-p)(2pqd)] + q^2[(-2p)^2(\alpha + pd)^2]\\ = p^2[4q^2 + (\alpha^2 + q^2d^2 - 2\alpha qd] + 2pq[\alpha^2(q-p)^2 + \\ (pqd)^2 + 2\alpha (q-p) (2pqd)] + q^2[4p^2(\alpha^2 + p^2d^2 + 2a\alpha pd] \\ = 8p^2q^2\alpha^2 + 4p^2q^2d^2(q^2) + 4p^2q^2d^2(p^2) - 8p^2q^2\alpha d(q) \\ + 8p^2q^2\alpha d(p) + 4p^2q^2d^2 2(p-q) + 2pq \alpha^2 (q^2+ p^2 -2pq) + 8p^2q^2 \alpha d(q) - 8 p^2q^2 \alpha d(p)\\ = 8p^2q^2\alpha^2 + 4p^2q^2d^2(p^2+2pq+q^2) + 2pq\alpha^2 (q^2+p^2-2pq)\\ = 4p^2q^2d^2 + 2pq\alpha^2 (4pq + q^2+p^2-2pq)\\ = 2pq\alpha^2 + (2pqd)^2\\ = \sigma^2_g\\ \end{align*}\]

Regression Sum of Squares

\[\begin{align*} \hat{b}_1 \sum f_i x_iy_i = \alpha (2pq\alpha)\\ = 2pq\alpha^2\\ = \sigma^2_a \end{align*}\]

Residual Sum of Squares

\[\begin{align*} \sum f_i\hat{e}^2_i \\ =p^2(-2q^2d)^2 + 2pq(2pqd)^2 + q^2(-2p^2d)^2\\ = 4p^2q^4d^2 + 8p^3q^3d^2 + 4p^4q^2d^2\\ = 4p^2q^2d^2(q^2+2pq+p^2)\\ = 4p^2q^2d^2\\ = (2pqd)^2\\ = \sigma^2_d \end{align*}\]

Now, we can summarize it as:

Genotype Genotypic value (Y) Freq #alleles (X) y x \(\hat{y}\) \(\hat{y}\)
AA Y₁ = u + a p² 2 \(2q(\alpha - dq)\) 2q 2qα \(-2q^2d\)
Aa Y₂ = u + d 2pq 1 \(\alpha(q-p) + 2pqd\) q-p α(q-p) 2pqd
aa Y₃ = u - a q² 0 \(-2p(\alpha+pd)\) -2p -2pα \(-2p^2d\)

Summarizing some definitions

  • Phenotypic value: observed value for a given trait, that contains genetic and environmental source of variations
  • Genotypic value: phenotypic value after removing the environmental term
  • Additive value or Genetic value or Breeding value: genetic value of an individual, predicted by the allele (gamete) from and individuals, that can be estimated using the Biometric Model
  • Dominance (or deviation) value: deviation originated from interaction between two alleles from the same locus
  • Also relevant:
    • Values are attributed to the individuals
    • Effects (gene action for example) are related to the alleles

Hands-on

Simulation

  • Tow example showing how to fit simple regression models in R.
  • Results using the lm function and formulas are the same.
# Simulation
x=1:20
n = length(x)
a = 0.2
b = 0.3
sigma=0.5
y = a + b*x + sigma*rnorm(n)

# Fitting the model
b = cov(x,y)/var(x)
a = mean(y) - b*mean(x)

# Using the lm function
summary(lm(y~x))

Example of Biometric Model

Let’s represent the biometric model in R. For that, we need to define the genotypic values (“predicted value”) and the breeding values (“expected values”) and the allele frequencies.

Exercise

  • Fit the same model, but modifying the values of a and d
  • Fit the same model, but modifying the allele frequencies

R code to fit a Biometric Regression Model

# Biometric Plot
a = 1; 
d = 0*a
p = 0.5; q = 1 - p

alpha <- a + d*(q - p)
a1a1 <- 2*alpha*q
a1a2 <- (q-p)*alpha
a2a2 <- -2*p*alpha

plot(c(0, 1, 2), c(-a, d, a), xlab="Genotype",ylab="", cex.lab=1, xaxt="n", pch=16, cex=1, col="black",
     main = paste("a=", a, ",", "d=",d, "\n", "p=",p,"q=",q)); 
axis(1, at=c(0, 1, 2), labels=c("A2A2", "A1A2", "A1A1")); 
#mtext("Breeding Value", side = 4, line = 1, cex=1, col="black"); 
mtext("Genotypic Value", side = 2, line = 2, cex=1, col="black")
points(c(0, 1, 2), c(a2a2, a1a2, a1a1), cex=2, col="black")
lines(c(0, 1, 2), c(a2a2, a1a2, a1a1), lwd=2, col="black")

Conclusion: \(\alpha\) is not only a function of the breeding values, but also depends on the allele frequencies in the population. As pointed out by Lynch and Walsh (1998), with the dominance, the phenotype effect of a gene substitution depend on the status of the unsubstituted allele. If A1 is dominant , then \(\alpha\) will be inflated relative to the case off additivity if A2is rare, but diminished if A2 is common.
